metrics_conclusion: In terms of chords and melody, Battle Champion Iris is more complex than the typical song, having above average scores in Chord Complexity, Melodic Complexity, Chord Progression Novelty and Chord-Bass Melody.
key_conclusion: Battle Champion Iris has sections analyzed in the following keys: G Mixolydian,  and G Major.  Click on the linked cheat sheets for popular chords, chord progressions, downloadable midi files and more!

metadata.editComments: I didn't transcribe the entire section because everything from here to the pre-chorus is basically just riffed over a tonic chord. The music file in the game notates this tempo as 96 BPM, but I transcribed it at 192 since it has a double time feel and that's how most of the chords move.

Although the root of G is mostly consistent throughout the song, the modes used change constantly. You can see that here since the 7th of the tonic keeps changing. The intro was easier to keep in G mixolydian because all of the Fs were natural. But the song typically defaults to major, which I'm doing here. The original data from the game doesn't appear to use a meter change, but you can tell it's there by looking at the chords and phrase length. Without it, the music still ends up on the beat when it returns to 4 because there were an even 4 measures in 6. Or 4 measures in 3 if you're at the original tempo.

The Bm7 flat 9 is technically the sum of two triads that only make sense when you put them together. There's a few other spots like that where the chord isn't exactly played as is in the measure, but the notes played add up to it in that space. The end of this tab is a good example of the riffs that basically have no chords that I was talking about in the intro. I'd basically just be notating a melody if I transcribed them.
